# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: turborepo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:turborepo/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:turborepo/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:turborepo/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:turborepo/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] An automated incremental computing tool is a specialised program analysis tool for optimization.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] Some approaches to incremental computing are specialized, while others are general purpose.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] Specialized approaches require the programmer to explicitly specify the algorithms and data structures that will be used to preserve unchanged sub-calculations.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] General-purpose approaches, on the other hand, use language, compiler, or algorithmic techniques to give incremental behavior to otherwise non-incremental programs.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] Given a computation $C=f(x_{1},x_{2},\dots x_{n})$ and a potential change $x_{j}:=\Delta _{x_{j}}$ , we can insert code before the change occurs (the pre-derivative) and after the change (the post-derivative) to update the value of C faster than rerunning f .
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] Paige has written down a list of rules for formal differentiation of programs in SUBSETL.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] In database systems such as DBToaster, views are defined with relational algebra.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] *Incremental view maintenance* statically analyzes relational algebra to create update rules that quickly maintain the view in the presence of small updates, such as insertion of a row.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] Incremental computation can be achieved by building a dependency graph of all the data elements that may need to be recalculated, and their dependencies.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] The elements that need to be updated when a single element changes are given by the transitive closure of the dependency relation of the graph.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] In other words, if there is a path from the changed element to another element, the latter may be updated (depending on whether the change eventually reaches the element).
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] The dependency graph may need to be updated as dependencies change, or as elements are added to, or removed from, the system.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] It is used internally by the implementation, and does not typically need to be displayed to the user.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] Partial evaluation can be combined with other incremental computing techniques.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] With cycles in the dependency graph, a single pass through the graph may not be sufficient to reach a fixed point.
[src:turborepo/incremental-computing] In some cases, complete re-evaluation of a system is semantically equivalent to incremental evaluation, and may be more efficient in practice if not in theory.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In version-control systems, a **monorepo** or **monorepository** ("mono" meaning 'single' and "repo" being short for 'repository') is a software-development strategy in which the code for a number of projects is stored in the same repository.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] This practice dates back to at least the early 2000s, when it was commonly called a shared codebase.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Google, Meta, Microsoft, Uber, Airbnb, and Twitter all employ very large monorepos with varying strategies to scale build systems and version control software with a large volume of code and daily changes.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] A related concept is a monolithic application, but whereas a monolith combines its sub-projects into one large project, a monorepo may contain multiple independent projects.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In a multiple repository environment where multiple projects depend on a third-party dependency, that dependency might be downloaded or built multiple times.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In a monorepo the build can be easily optimized, as referenced dependencies all exist in the same codebase.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] When projects that work together are contained in separate repositories, releases need to sync which versions of one project work with the other.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In a monorepo this problem can be negated, since developers may change multiple projects atomically.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Since developers have access to the entire project, refactors can ensure that every piece of the project continues to function after a refactor.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] teams can improve projects being worked on by other teams.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Although not required, some monorepo builds use one version number across all projects in the repository.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] With split repositories, access to a repository can be granted based upon need.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] A monorepo allows read access to all software in the project, possibly presenting new security issues.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Note that there are versioning systems in which this limitation is not an issue.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] is used, it's possible to download any part of the repo (even a single directory), and path-based authorization can be used to restrict access to certain parts of a repository.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] With split repositories, you fetch only the project you are interested in by default.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] This can take up a significant amount of storage space.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] doing so defeats some of the advantages of a monorepo.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Companies with large projects have come across hurdles with monorepos, specifically concerning build tools and version control systems.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Google's monorepo, speculated to be the largest in the world, meets the classification of an ultra-large-scale system and must handle tens of thousands of contributions every day in a repository over 80 terabytes in size.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Companies using or switching to existing version control software found that software could not efficiently handle the amount of data required for a large monorepo.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Facebook and Microsoft chose to contribute to or fork existing version control software Mercurial and Git respectively, while Google eventually created their own version control system.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] For more than ten years, Google had relied on Perforce hosted on a single machine.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In 2005 Google's build servers could get locked up to 10 minutes at a time.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Google improved this to 30 seconds–1 minute in 2010.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Due to scaling issues, Google eventually developed its own in-house distributed version control system dubbed Piper.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Facebook ran into performance issues with the version control system Mercurial and made upstream contributions to the client, and in January 2014 made it faster than a competing solution in Git.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In May 2017 Microsoft announced that virtually all of its Windows engineers use a Git monorepo.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] In the transition, Microsoft made substantial upstream contributions to the Git client to remove unnecessary file access and improve handling of large files with Virtual File System for Git.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Few build tools work well in a monorepo, and flows where builds and continuous integration testing of the entire repository are performed upon check-in will cause performance problems.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] A build system that processes dependencies as a directed graph (such as Buck, Bazel, Please, or Pants) solves this by compartmentalizing each build or test to the active area of development.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Twitter began development of Pants in 2011, as both Facebook's Buck and Google's Bazel were closed-source at the time.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Twitter open-sourced Pants in 2012 under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:turborepo/monorepo] Please is a Go-based build system; it was developed in 2016 by Thought Machine, whose developers were both inspired by Google's Bazel and dissatisfied with Facebook's Buck.
[src:turborepo/repo] Turborepo is a high-performance build system for JavaScript and TypeScript codebases.
[src:turborepo/repo] It is designed for scaling monorepos and also makes workflows in single-package workspaces faster, too.
[src:turborepo/repo] From individual developers to the largest enterprise engineering organizations in the world, Turborepo is saving years of engineering time and millions of dollars in compute costs through a lightweight approach to optimizing the tasks you need to run in your repository.
[src:turborepo/repo] Monorepos have many advantages - but **they struggle to scale**.
[src:turborepo/repo] Each workspace has its own test suite, its own linting, and its own build process.
[src:turborepo/repo] A single monorepo might have **thousands of tasks to execute**.
[src:turborepo/repo] (A representation of a typical monorepo.
[src:turborepo/repo] The first application took 110 seconds to complete its tasks.
[src:turborepo/repo] The second application took 140 seconds to complete its tasks.
[src:turborepo/repo] These slowdowns can dramatically affect the way your teams build software, especially at scale.
[src:turborepo/repo] Feedback loops need to be fast so developers can deliver high-quality code quickly.
[src:turborepo/repo] Additionally, task scheduling can be difficult in a monorepo.
[src:turborepo/repo] You may need to build, *then* test, *then* lint...
[src:turborepo/repo] Turborepo **schedules your tasks for maximum speed**, parallelizing work across all available cores.
[src:turborepo/repo] Turborepo can be **adopted incrementally** and you can **add it to any repository in just a few minutes**.
[src:turborepo/repo] It uses the `package.json` scripts you've already written, the dependencies you've already declared, and a single `turbo.json` file.
[src:turborepo/repo] You can **use it with any package manager**, like `npm`, `yarn` or `pnpm` since Turborepo leans on the conventions of the npm ecosystem.
[src:turborepo/repo] We will do our best to keep jargon to a minimum - but there are some need-to-know words that will be important to understand as you read through the docs.
[src:turborepo/repo] We've created a glossary page to help you out in case you're learning about these terms.
[src:turborepo/repo] If you have questions about anything related to Turborepo, you're always welcome to ask the community on GitHub Discussions, Vercel Community, and Twitter.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:turborepo/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:turborepo/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:turborepo/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:turborepo/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:turborepo/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:turborepo/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:turborepo/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:turborepo/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:turborepo/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:turborepo/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:turborepo/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:turborepo/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:turborepo/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:turborepo/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:turborepo/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:turborepo/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:turborepo/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:turborepo/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:turborepo/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:turborepo/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:turborepo/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:turborepo/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:turborepo/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:turborepo/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:turborepo/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:turborepo/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:turborepo/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:turborepo/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:turborepo/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:turborepo/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:turborepo/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:turborepo/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:turborepo/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:turborepo/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:turborepo/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:turborepo/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:turborepo/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:turborepo/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:turborepo/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:turborepo/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:turborepo/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:turborepo/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:turborepo/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:turborepo/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:turborepo/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
